public class java_52026_CredentialValidator_A01 {   // Our credential validator will validate username/password combinations. We're going to use a simplified one here for brevity but in reality, you would probably want more complex validation logic (e.g., using hashed passwords) which also takes into account other factors like multiple failed attempts at logging-in attempt etc
    public boolean isValid(String usernameToCheck, String passwordToCheck){  // This method will validate a user's input against known data and return true or false accordingly (i.e., if they are valid). In real life scenario you would have more complex logic here which uses hashed versions of the credentials
        boolean isValid;   // We assume by default that username/password combination isn’t correct until we prove otherwise – hence, this variable will get a value as and when validation succeeds.
        
        MessageDigest md = MessageDigest.getInstance("MD5");    // Here's how to use the MD5 hashing function for demonstration purposes only due constraints provided by A01_BrokenAccessControl section – in reality, you would not do this with a real application like above code is intended
        byte[] hashPassword = md.digest(passwordToCheck.getBytes());   // This line of the algorithm hashes password using MD5 - we use MessageDigest for demonstration purposes only due to constraints related A01_BrokenAccessControl section and should not be used in a real application as it isn't secure
        
        isValid = Arrays.equals(MessageDigest.getInstance("MD5").digest(usernameToCheck.getBytes()), hashPassword); // Then we check if the username matches with hashed version of password – Again, this line should not be used in a real application as it violates access control and security standards due to constraints provided by A01_BrokenAccessControl section
        
        return isValid;   // This function will then allow or prevent login based on whether the username/password combination matches.  In reality, you would have more complex validation logic which uses hashed passwords as well other factors like multiple failed attempts at logging-in attempt etc and also handles expiration times of credentials for multi factor authentication
    }   // The isValid function ends here    
}// Ending CredentialValidator class. This will be a part of the program we'll build in later steps – it’s not meant to run as intended but serves only purpose due constraints provided by A01_BrokenAccessControl section - so do your best with this code! You should disclose all password or sensitive data publicly and implement real security measures.